<header class="header">
  <h1>Bush Beans vs Pole Beans</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Choose bean varieties based on harvest pattern, space, support, and season length.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    <strong>Bush beans are compact and often earlier, while pole beans climb, need support, and can produce over a longer harvest window.</strong>
  </p>
</header>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Quick Answer</h2>
  <p>
    Choose bush beans for short seasons, small gardens, easy planting, and quick harvests. Choose pole beans when you have vertical support and want a longer picking season.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Bush beans:</strong> compact plants, faster harvest, no trellis needed</li>
    <li><strong>Pole beans:</strong> climbing plants, longer harvest, support required</li>
    <li><strong>Short-season fit:</strong> bush beans are usually safer</li>
    <li><strong>Main decision:</strong> quick concentrated harvest vs longer vertical production</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What Bush Beans Are Best For</h2>
  <p>
    Bush beans are best when you want a simple, reliable crop that does not need a trellis. They are usually easier to fit into short seasons because many varieties mature quickly and produce over a compact window.
  </p>
  <p>
    They are also useful for succession planting. Instead of relying on one long harvest, you can sow more than once if your season allows.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What Pole Beans Are Best For</h2>
  <p>
    Pole beans are best when you want to use vertical space and harvest over a longer period. They can be very productive, but they need a trellis, fence, or other support.
  </p>
  <p>
    In short seasons, pole beans can still work, but they may take longer to reach full production than bush beans. That makes planting time and variety choice more important.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Which Type Is Better for Short Seasons?</h2>
  <p>
    Bush beans are usually the safer first choice for short seasons. They mature quickly, need less setup, and can produce a useful harvest before the season gets tight.
  </p>
  <p>
    Pole beans are better when the season is long enough for vines to climb and keep producing. If frost arrives early, the long harvest advantage may be cut short.
  </p>
</section>

