<section class="card">
  <h2>Common Mistakes When Comparing Bean Types</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Planting pole beans without support:</strong> climbing beans need a structure.</li>
    <li><strong>Expecting bush beans to crop all season:</strong> they often produce in a shorter window.</li>
    <li><strong>Planting into cold soil:</strong> beans germinate poorly when conditions are too cool.</li>
    <li><strong>Ignoring harvest frequency:</strong> regular picking keeps many beans productive.</li>
    <li><strong>Choosing pole beans in a very short season:</strong> they may not have enough time to hit peak production.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Best Strategy for Home Gardens</h2>
  <p>
    In short seasons, start with bush beans. If you have room, add pole beans for a longer harvest once you know your season can support them. In small gardens, compact bush beans can be the simplest and most reliable option.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Plan Around Your Local Season</h2>
  <p>
    Beans need warm soil and frost-free weather. A quick bush bean can fit into many short seasons, but late sowings and cold starts still reduce the harvest window.
  </p>
